This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:36 PM Defendant Norman Wayne Cutbank III appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Ellen Denise Craker appears with Defendant. Attorney Angela Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. Address verified as correct. Receives complaint, wavies reading, requests preliminary hearing.  State requests $10,0000 cash, no contact with Victim 1. Offense committed while being housed in Douglas County jail on another inmate. Cites priors. 
Attorney Craker indicates already has $50,000 cash bail in another file. Additional amount not necessary. Already can't post the $50,000. Asks for nominal cash amount. 
Court orders $5,000 cash, with conditions of no contact with Victim 1.
